bib.title: Feeding of Rh and Ag isomers in fast-neutron-inducedreactions

free_txt: US Army Research Laboratory, Adelphi, Maryland
Experiment performed at Alamos Neutron
spallation neutron source on the 60R flight path.
Compiled by S.H.
The gamma rays produced in the bombardment of
the 103Rh and 109Ag targets by neutrons were measured
with the GEANIE spectrometer. GEANIE comprised 10
Compton suppressed planar Ge detectors (low-energy
photon spectrometers) and 10 Compton suppressed
coaxial Ge detectors. Several HPGe detectors were not
used for analysis because of insufficient energy
resolution or frequent gain shift during experiment.
No information on source of uncertainties
Experiment performed at Alamos Neutron
spallation neutron source on the 60R flight path.
The neutrons were produced in a natural W
spallation target driven by an 800 MeV proton beam.
Energy of incident neutrons was determined
using time-of-flight method. The beam time structure
consisted of 625 mu-s long macropulses at 40 Hz rate.
Each macropulse contained approximately 340
micropulses spaced every 1.8 mu-s. At this
micropulse+-spacing, wrap-around problems (time
overlap of high-energy neutrons of one pulse with
lower-energy neutrons of the previous pulse start at
En < 0.6 MeV and below.
Cross section for
production of 846.8 keV line on natural Fe i.e. sum
56Fe(n,n'g) + 57Fe(n,2ng) with value 705 mb was taken
as monitor cross section
During two
days of the experiment, two natural Fe 2.5 cm square
foils, 0.05 mm thick each, were placed, in front and
in back of the 103Rh foils. Known cross section at En
= 14.5 MeV of the strong 846.8-keV gamma ray used to
normalize the cross sections
Natural Rh sample consisted of two 2.5cm square foil
of 1.58 g of 103Rh.
